&gt;
&gt; Well it is fast and it also isn&#39;t.

You&#39;re right of course and have clearly done more work with nns than I
have.  However, I am inclinded to argue that for the current architectures
sitting on most of our desktops, it is fast.  I realize this is why many
attempts at making custom hardware have been carried out with some success
(actually, I have no idea how much success).  I would imagine that given
the sort of flexibility you almost always want (have any of us ever
finished a network simulator and said, Eureka! It&#39;s perfect!?) that this
sort of approach is up there for speed/flexibility trade off.  But I
imagine it is this sort of thing that was the stuff of your philisophical
discussion and when I get a chance I would like to read it.

I am consoled to hear that the &quot;collection&quot; stage is the bottle neck.  I
don&#39;t know how much more time I could spend staring at the lines of code:

if(enabled)
  sink+=weight*pParent-&gt;source

looking for optimizations

Also - and I&#39;m getting ahead of myself here as I had hoped to get into
some of these discussions a little further into my work - I feel a lot of
the speed from this sort of architecture comes from the ability to do
topographical transformations in place without serializing the network
into a genome.  When I do serialize I see performance hits there.

Thanks for your thoughts,

jeff


